The dot product and cross product are two fundamental operations in vector algebra. The dot product of two vectors is a scalar quantity that is equal to the product of their magnitudes and the cosine of the angle between them. The cross product of two vectors is a vector quantity that is perpendicular to both of the input vectors and has a magnitude equal to the product of their magnitudes and the sine of the angle between them.

In graphics environments, the dot product is often used to calculate the angle between two vectors. For example, it can be used to determine the angle between the surface normal and the light direction to calculate the shading of a 3D object. The dot product can also be used to project one vector onto another.

The cross product is often used to calculate the normal vector of a plane or the axis of rotation between two vectors. For example, it can be used to calculate the normal vector of a polygon to determine its orientation in 3D space. The cross product can also be used to calculate the torque on a rotating object.

